The Two Poland
The European Parliament has recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner and former Minister of Foreign Affairs - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another statement that he was not a secret police agent at the time of communism.
European Parliament members have spoken of a "witch hunt" regarding the Polish government's behavior, and Geremek stated that the law on lustration [décommunisation] constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, the Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and stirring up anti-Polish sentiment.
Communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A recent Constitutional Court decision on May 11 has largely invalidated the law on lustration, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
But this law is part of a general policy of the Polish government, which has only one goal: to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began ?
Each revolution passes through two phases: first a fight for liberty, then a struggle for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul by which man expresses what is best in him, while the second unleashes the worst: envy, intrigues, avarice, suspicion, and the desire for vengeance.
The revolution sparked by the Polish Solidarity trade union followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into clandestinity when martial law was decreed in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in the open in 1989, in the wake of Gorbachev's "perestroika".
During the negotiations that brought an end to the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship across the entire Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a policy of compromise rather than vengeance, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between the powerful victors and the oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and market economy.
But not everyone has followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity avengers, post-communist provincial troublemakers, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and the circles surrounding Radio Maryja, a mouthpiece for ethnic-clerical fundamentalism.
We see ominous signs everywhere: the authority of the judiciary is being eroded, the independence of the Constitutional Court is being called into question, officials are being bribed, and the office of prosecutor is being politicized.
Every day, social life is subject to repressive regulation.
Why all of this ?
Each successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought public liberties, but also increased delinquency, a market economy, as well as the risks of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, alongside the emergence of a dynamic middle class accompanied by a deepening income gap.
She opened Poland to Europe, but it has also induced the fear of the stranger and the fear of a massive invasion of Western culture.
For the losers of the Polish revolution of 1989, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In the large enterprises, the Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they have conquered.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered to belong to the State, but the State took care of them.
In a world of freedom, no one is there to take care of us.
It's in this atmosphere of anxiety that the current coalition governs, combining the conservative potion of George W. Bush with the centralism of Vladimir Putin.
For the veterans of Solidarity, the end of the dictatorship was supposed to be a stepping stone to the firmament.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished and the virtuous militants of Solidarity were not rewarded.
This sense of injustice has given rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed as much against old enemies as against old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was Poland's greatest achievement in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland was in need of a moral revolution that would make crimes unpunished no more, virtue rewarded, and injustices rectified.
After their victory in the 2005 general elections, the parties of the losers chose a method: a major purge.
According to initial estimates, lustration is expected to take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names has been found in the security services' archives; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people targeted by lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be fired and barred from practicing their profession for ten years.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be fired and barred from practicing their profession for ten years.
The Archbishop of Krakow, Cardinal Dziwisz, reminds us that there is no room for "revenge, vengeance, disrespect for human dignity, and baseless accusations".
Never before since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The goal of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a witch hunt, proven or unproven, for belonging to the secret police.
If this witch hunt had been organized in 1990, neither Leszek Balcerowicz's economic reforms nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would be neither a member of NATO, nor of the European Union.
Today, two Polands face each other.
Poland of suspicion, fear, and vengeance is fighting Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - made of openness and tolerance, of John Paul II and Czeslaw Milosz, of my friends from the underground and prison - must prevail.
I believe the Polish are once again going to defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The Constitutional Court's decision gives hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will not destroy either what gave it birth, the will for freedom, or what it has engendered, a democratic State.
